    </visualElement>
    <visualElement>
      <elementName>Text</elementName>
      <elementAttributes>
        <entry>
          <string>Description</string>
          <string>We manage the state machine and
decode the current state.</string>
        </entry>
      </elementAttributes>
      <pos x="-5820" y="-2240"/>
    </visualElement>
    <visualElement>
      <elementName>Text</elementName>
      <elementAttributes>
        <entry>
          <string>Description</string>
          <string>JTAG TAPs manage serial communication between a circuit and an outside device.
The device pulses TCK while holding TMS high or low to navigate a state machine
internal to the TAP. A good diagram of this state machine can be found at:
https://adaptivesupport.amd.com/s/article/3203
(If this goes down or moves, I&apos;m sure you know how to look things up.)

The point of the state machine is to manage shifting, capturing, and updating
two locations. One of these is the ir (instruction register), and the other is the dr
(data register). Of these two, the ir is the only one that is actually a register. The
dr is a more meta construct that represents a multitude of registers, of which
an active one is selected via the value in ir. To additionally complicate things, not
every member of dr is required to be a physical register. Do you know the Unix
&quot;everything-is-a-file&quot; mentality? That&apos;s sort of how the members of dr work. 
Technically, they can be normal registers, but most have special behaviours.

The dmi, for example, is a readable and writeable communication channel
defined by the RISC-V debug specification, found here:
https://riscv.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/riscv-debug-release.pdf

The dmi is the singular outpoint of this particular TAP, and the only
way for attached debuggers to communicate with the CPU&apos;s debug module.</string>
        </entry>
      </elementAttributes>
      <pos x="-7880" y="-2780"/>
    </visualElement>
    <visualElement>
      <elementName>Rectangle</elementName>
      <elementAttributes>
        <entry>
          <string>textFontSize</string>
          <int>48</int>
        </entry>
        <entry>
          <string>RectHeight</string>
          <int>33</int>
        </entry>
        <entry>
          <string>Label</string>
          <string>Understanding the TAP</string>
        </entry>
        <entry>
          <string>RectWidth</string>
